<TITLE> Women movement leader Hena Das dies </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 20 (bdnews24.com)Veteran women movements leader and Communist Party of Bangladesh central committee member Hena Das, 85, died on Monday morning at Bangabandhu Sheikh Mujib Medical University hospital. Ruhin Hossain Prince, CPB central committee member, told bdnews24.com over telephone that she died at 11:30am. Her body will be cremated after her daughter arrives from Germany, Prince said. The body will now be kept in a mortuary. Ruhin added that Hena was a member of CPB's control commission, prior to which she had been a member of the CPB Politburo. She had been a pioneer joining anti-British demonstrations and political movements, subsequently taking part in all secular democratic movements in an independent country. A press release from the CPB said her cremation will be held on July 23. Before the cremation the body will be kept at the CPB office to pay respect at 10am, teachers' association office at Segunbagicha at 10:45am, central office of Mohila Somiti at 11am and at Shaheed Minar at 12pm. Then the body will be taken to Narayangang for cremating. A forerunner in all women's liberation movements, Hena Das was also a teacher. Das suffering for long from old-age complications was admitted to LabAid Hospital on July 18, a CPB press release said on Sunday. After showing slight improvement of her condition, Hena fell again seriously ill on Sunday morning, when she was shifted to the BSMMU hospital. Das left two daughters behind, who are both doctors, and a multitude of well wishers. In her death prime minister Sheikh Hasina, CPB president Manjurul Ahsan Khan, secretary Mujahidul Islam Selim, JSD president Hasanul Haque Inu, acting general secretary Shirin Sultana, Mohila Parishad president Ayesha Khanom, general secretary Maleka Banu gave separate condolence messages and prayed for peace of her soul. Chhatra Union, Jubo Union, Krishak Samity, Khetmajur Samity, Democratic Lawyers' Association, Jatiya Sromik Jote, Bangabandhu Shangskritik Jote along with other organisations also expressed their condolence. bdnew
